## raw 109 — adversarial co-evolution probe
@r109_raw_id raw_109_adversarial_co_evolution_probe
@r109_raw_concept Two systems (defender + attacker) evolve in lockstep; each adapts to the other's current best policy. In hexa-lang context: defender = parser/lexer pipeline; attacker = adversarial source-text generator that maximizes parser-crash / mis-parse rate.
@r109_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/regression/  # NEW candidate file: parser_adversarial_coevolution.hexa — fuzzer pair: malformed-source generator + parser; loop generator until parser stable, retrain generator against fixed parser version (co-evolution cadence ≥3 rounds).
@r109_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/regression/parser_resume_empty_lhs.hexa  # existing regression seed — extend to declare @co_evolution_round_index header so generator can target uncovered failure modes.
@r109_minimal_reproducer_pointer /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/parser.hexa header — extend with @co_evolution_loop annotation declaring (a) attacker-update cadence (b) parser-rebuild trigger (c) crash-rate ceiling falsifier.
@r109_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r109-parser-adversarial-coevolution
@r109_dependencies self/parser.hexa stable (already self-hosting per example/self_host_parser.hexa) — co-evolution loop is a test-harness extension, not a parser refactor.
@r109_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r109-parser-adversarial-coevolution_omega_cycle  (downstream)

## raw 110 — systematic ablation, causal core
@r110_raw_id raw_110_systematic_ablation_causal_core
@r110_raw_concept N-component system → enumerate all 2^N - 1 non-empty subsets, measure capability on each, isolate component(s) whose removal causes >X% capability-drop. Causal core = minimal subset that preserves ≥(1-ε)·capability_full. In hexa-lang context: parser productions / stdlib functions are the components; self-host bootstrap success is the capability metric.
@r110_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/  # NEW candidate file: parser_ablation_causal_core.hexa — for each parser production rule, mask it, attempt self-host build (`hexa self/main.hexa`); record build-pass / build-fail; emit causal-core ranking.
@r110_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/example/self_host_parser.hexa  # existing self-host scaffold — extend with --ablate-rule <rule_name> CLI flag enabling subset-build loop.
@r110_minimal_reproducer_pointer self/parser.hexa — currently parses unconditionally; add ablate-mask driver above (mask = noop the matched production, return generic error).
@r110_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r110-parser-ablation-causal-core
@r110_dependencies self/parser.hexa rule list enumerable (probe header for rule registry); self-host build rc observable (via hexa exit code).
@r110_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r110-parser-causal-core-ablation_omega_cycle  (downstream)

## raw 112 — categorical functor composition
@r112_raw_id raw_112_categorical_functor_composition
@r112_raw_concept F: C→D, G: D→E composable iff codomain(F) = domain(G); composition (G∘F) preserves structure. In hexa-lang: parser combinators ARE functors over token-stream category; combinator composition law = (parse_a ∘ parse_b) = parse_seq(a, b) iff types align.
@r112_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/parser.hexa  # extend with @functor_composition_law header — every combinator pair must declare composability witness (codomain-of-A = domain-of-B) OR fail at parser-construction time (not at runtime).
@r112_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/  # NEW candidate file: parser_combinator_functor_law.hexa — assert (parse_a ∘ parse_b) ≡ parse_seq(a, b) on N=20 randomly-generated combinator pairs (raw 73 deterministic verifier — fixed seed).
@r112_minimal_reproducer_pointer self/parser.hexa combinator definitions (probe for parse_*, alt_*, seq_* functions) — annotate each with @domain @codomain @functor_id.
@r112_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r112-parser-combinator-functor-laws
@r112_dependencies parser combinator surface enumerated; type ascription on combinator inputs/outputs (probe self/parser.hexa for existing type sigs).
@r112_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r112-parser-functor-composition-law_omega_cycle  (downstream)

## raw 114 — bisimulation behavioral equivalence
@r114_raw_id raw_114_bisimulation_behavioral_equivalence
@r114_raw_concept Two systems are behaviorally equivalent iff every observable transition of one is matched by the other (Park's bisimulation). In hexa-lang: candidate parser ≈ reference parser iff bisimulation holds on identical token-stream inputs producing identical AST outputs (or identical error positions on malformed inputs).
@r114_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/  # NEW candidate file: parser_bisimulation_check.hexa — drive both parser_v_old + parser_v_new on identical corpus, assert AST-identity (or error-position-identity); report counter-example token-stream on FAIL.
@r114_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/parser.hexa  # add @law_bisimulation_with_reference header — declare reference-parser pointer (e.g. example/self_host_parser.hexa) and assert any optimization preserves bisimulation.
@r114_minimal_reproducer_pointer test/t_parser_select_attr.hexa — existing parser test; extend pattern to drive two parser versions in lockstep on the same fixture corpus.
@r114_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r114-parser-bisimulation-checker
@r114_dependencies AST equality predicate (probe self/ast.hexa for existing ast_eq); error-position serialization (probe self/parser.hexa for error format).
@r114_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r114-parser-bisimulation-equivalence_omega_cycle  (downstream)

## raw 118 — recursive self-application fixpoint
@r118_raw_id raw_118_recursive_self_application_fixpoint
@r118_raw_concept f(x) = x fixpoint: system applied to itself converges to a stable point. In hexa-lang: self-host parser parses its own source → produces AST → emits source from AST → re-parses → AST should be identical (parse-print-parse fixpoint, level-1) OR self-host compiler compiled by itself produces a binary identical to the binary that compiled it (bootstrap fixpoint, level-2).
@r118_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/example/self_host_parser.hexa  # already-existing self-host scaffold; formalize as @fixpoint_level_1 (parse→print→parse identity) by adding round-trip assertion.
@r118_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/main.hexa  # self-host compiler entrypoint; extend with @fixpoint_level_2 (bootstrap binary stability) — emit compiled-binary sha256, compare against prior-stage sha256, gate on equality after N=2 bootstrap rounds.
@r118_minimal_reproducer_pointer example/self_host_parser.hexa — already self-hosting parsing; round-trip assert is one diff-line addition once printer is identified (probe self/ for printer / pretty_print / emit functions).
@r118_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r118-self-host-fixpoint-protocol
@r118_dependencies AST printer (parse→print direction); deterministic build (env-stable hash — probe build/ + bin/ for canonical compile invocation; see existing aot-cache-canonical-path raw 145 work for path-canonicalization wins).
@r118_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r118-self-host-fixpoint-rounds_omega_cycle  (downstream)

## raw 126 — meta-rule self-host stability
@r126_raw_id raw_126_meta_rule_self_host_stability
@r126_raw_concept Meta-rules (rules-about-rules) define system; system applies meta-rules to itself; if meta-rules survive self-application unchanged, system is meta-stable. In hexa-lang: language semantics rules (.spec or .grammar) are themselves valid hexa-lang programs; running the parser on its own grammar definition emits an AST whose meta-structure matches the source-of-truth grammar.
@r126_hexalang_landing_primary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/self/_specs_quicktest.hexa  # existing specs quicktest — extend to drive parser over self/parser.hexa SOURCE and assert meta-rule extraction matches a pre-declared canonical grammar table.
@r126_hexalang_landing_secondary /Users/ghost/core/hexa-lang/test/  # NEW candidate file: meta_rule_self_host_stability.hexa — N=2 application of grammar-extractor to itself, assert fixed-point reached (raw 118 fixpoint applied to grammar layer specifically).
@r126_minimal_reproducer_pointer self/_specs_quicktest.hexa — already exercises spec-style assertions; meta-rule loop is a higher-order test layered on top.
@r126_tracking_id hexa-lang/issues/TBD-r126-meta-rule-grammar-stability
@r126_dependencies grammar-extractor primitive (NEW — probe self/ for any existing grammar dump utility; if absent, depends on raw 118 print-AST capability); canonical grammar table (NEW reference artifact).
@r126_witness_cycle_handle 2026-04-XX_r126-meta-rule-self-host-stability_omega_cycle  (downstream)

